625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>One of the most complex industries on=
 Earth needs radical change</strong></h3><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Let&#8217;s start w=
ith an enormous, and seemingly intractable, problem. </span><a href=3D"http=
s://substack.com/redirect/0f7249dc-39d5-476c-bc22-822e13828cba?r=3D9p0gt" r=
el=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">We need to bu=
ild 3.8 million more housing units</a><span> in the United States just to k=
eep up with the rate of household formation&#8212;</span><a href=3D"https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/786cc149-6ab7-4d98-a13e-1b3a8c344b5a?r=3D9p0gt" rel=
=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">we&#8217;re cur=
rently building at a rate of 1.5 million per year</a><span>. Add in the nee=
d for additional essential infrastructure, and </span><strong>construction =
output will likely double by the end of the decade.</strong></p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">To=
 keep up with the Paris agreements&#8212;and to stave off the worst-case cl=
imate scenario&#8212;the construction industry, like every other industry, =
needs to reduce its total carbon emissions by about 45% by 2030.&#160;</p><=
p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 =
1em 0;"><span>It doesn&#8217;t take a math genius to calculate that </span>=
<strong>in order to both double construction output and cut emissions almos=
t in half, all within the next 8 years, we need to slash per-project emissi=
ons by at least 70%.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>2030 is coming fast in cons=
truction time. Construction isn&#8217;t software and can&#8217;t be iterate=
d multiple times a day. Many in the industry work on one project at a time.=
 And given that new buildings take, from idea to occupancy, about 2 to 4 ye=
ars to complete, we need to make radical changes right now&#8212;leaving us=
 the next</span><strong> three to four</strong><span> iterative cycles to h=
it the 2030 targets.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px;=
 line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Oh&#8212;and building shit is=
 hard. You&#8217;re putting millions of dollars on the line for a </span><s=
trong>single digit profit margin</strong><span>, and, at the same time, dea=
ling with all of the challenges of a people business: mistakes are made, em=
ployees argue, and construction materials&#8212;well, we can only hope they=
 show up sometime. Let&#8217;s just say adding brand-new, untested products=
 to the mix isn&#8217;t something contractors hope for when they wake up.</=
span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; ma=
rgin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>If you aren&#8217;t concerned enough yet&#8230;</sp=
an><strong><span>real estate accounts for </span><a href=3D"https://substac=
k.com/redirect/9e721c48-b049-480e-8e4f-60d4ee29bb9e?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" sty=
le=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">38% of global greenhouse=
 gas emissions</a></strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Construction is a nec=
essary industry and its impact on society is real and lasting. Without cons=
truction, we don&#8217;t have hospitals, schools, housing or power. No stad=
iums, retail spaces, theaters, conference centers. Without construction we =
live in tents.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height:=
 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><strong>Bottom line: construction is a high carb=
on, low margin, essential industry.</strong><span> We can&#8217;t just cros=
s our fingers and hope it will decarbonize. We have to do the work. As two =
dads with kids whose lives will be shaped by the trajectory of the climate =
crisis, we feel we have a personal stake in doing this work&#8212;and, as s=
uccessful founders with experience in the construction and fintech industri=
es, we believe we have a unique angle on the solution to construction&#8217=
;s seemingly intractable carbon problem.</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a=
1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">We need to radi=
cally rethink how we approach construction. In order to make that happen, w=
e need to give everyone &#8211; from the bankers who finance construction p=
rojects, to the corporations that rent office space, to the ordinary people=
 who rent apartments &#8211; the information they need to easily identify c=
arbon-neutral buildings, and vote with their feet for lower-carbon options.=
 We need to align the financial incentives of this industry with the urgent=
 human need to address the climate crisis.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Two key things=
 need to happen to get the construction industry to go carbon-neutral withi=
n the next 8 years.</span><strong>&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: #1a=
1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>First, =
it needs to be easier for builders to </span><strong>find, evaluate, and im=
plement lower-carbon materials, and purchase high-quality carbon removal cr=
edits to offset the remaining emissions and get to carbon neutral. </strong=
><span>High-quality carbon credits serve two purposes.&#160; First, they fi=
nance projects that actually remove and sequester carbon.&#160; Second, the=
y capture the cost of the negative externality (carbon emissions) in the co=
st of the building.&#160; This not only helps us achieve our climate goals,=
 but also makes greener alternatives more cost competitive.&#160;&#160;&#16=
0;</span></p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Second, it needs to be easier for tenants and s=
takeholders</span><strong> to evaluate a building or project&#8217;s carbon=
 footprint.</strong><span> Much of this information is not well understood =
or is locked up in proprietary databases, hidden from mass consumption. Do =
you know how many metric tons of greenhouse gasses your apartment building =
emits each year? As one industry person put it, without public data, it is =
easy for tenants, bankers, investors and developers &#8220;to stay blissful=
ly ignorant of the mess they are making.&#8221;</span></p><p style=3D"color=
: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>Ba=
nks, investment firms, and companies with large real estate portfolios need=
 to stop the hot potato game of who owns a building&#8217;s carbon emission=
s. Building owners profit from their buildings, and we believe they are ult=
imately responsible for the carbon emitted. Tenants and other stakeholders =
should and are starting to demand better&#8212;</span><a href=3D"https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/c27dc66b-418f-4ab0-b8d9-ca0245af2ae4?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"=
" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">reports</a><span> a=
lready show that green-certified office buildings command rental premiums o=
f as much as 21%.&#160; Many of our early customers tell us that their buil=
dings are more valuable-upon sale and in the form of higher rents&#8211;if =
they are carbon neutral. So, do it for the earth, or do it for your bottom =
line. In the end, it doesn&#8217;t matter.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"><span>O=
ur company</span><a href=3D"https://substack.com/redirect/6104cd94-e2b0-408=
f-b6ed-3ba4f2c15f86?r=3D9p0gt" rel=3D"" style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; text-decor=
ation: underline;"> Carbon Title</a><span> offers a simple, transparent, co=
st-effective way to neutralize buildings&#8217; climate impact. Our platfor=
m empowers building owners, developers, and contractors to easily understan=
d a building&#8217;s CO2 emissions over time, purchase high-quality carbon =
credits, and apply carbon credits to achieve verifiable carbon neutrality.<=
/span></p><div class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-siz=
